segments.text: Tell us something about your early life, including the names of your parents, the dates and places, if you can, of their birth and death, the date and place of your birth, and the schools you attended before you came to A&M, and any things you can remember about your childhood that would be of interest.
Well, my father was W.R. Armstrong.
He was born...
in Dallas County, where White Rock Lake now is, on a farm.
His dad was farming there.
And my mother was born in Georgia.
And she went through school there in what would now be called Junior College, I guess.
My father didn't have any education except what he got in grade school.
But he did get a teaching certificate and taught school in Barnesville, which is in Johnson County.
And my mother was on a farm that belonged to her parents there.
And she played the piano in a little schoolhouse where they had church services.
And my dad happened to be teaching at that same school.
And that's where they met and married in 1897.
I was born on that farm, my grandmother's farm there, out east of Cleburne in 1898.
We lived out there a couple of years and moved into Cleburne where I started to school.
In 1907, my dad filed on some land out at
Portales, New Mexico.
This would be a homestead.
Homestead.
And we moved out there.
He was at that time working for the Santa Fe Railroad.
They furnished us an immigrant car in which he put all of our furniture and a couple of horses and a couple of cows and some pigs and chickens and what farm equipment he could get in there.
Hired a man to ride that car.
And we rode the day coach, of course.
We got passive on the Santa Fe.
Consequently, we had to go from Cleburne up to Winfield, Kansas, and back to Amarillo.
We couldn't ride the Fort Worth and Denver because our pass was not good on it.
But anyway, we got back through there and settled on a farm in Portales.
The first year there, I went to a little adobe one-room schoolhouse, about sixteen pupils, one teacher, and it was only a five-month school.
That's all the money they had, so they just wanted five months and quit.
Did the parents pay the teacher directly?
No, they hadI don't know just how they worked it.
I was just nine years old at the time, and I don't remember that.
But the next term, my father taught five months, and then he decided that that wasn't any place to raise a family in such a school as that, so he took us to Amarillo to put us in school in 1910.
Did the family then move to Amarillo?
The family moved to Amarillo, left the farm and moved to Amarillo, and he went to work for the Santa Fe Railroad in 1910.
And I went through school there, graduated from Amarillo High School in 1916.

And I didn't have enough money to go to college, and I decided to go to A&M because I could go there cheaper than anywhere else because I knew they wore uniforms and wouldn't have much clothing expense.
And I worked two years in order to get enough money to start down there.
What type of work did you do?
I went to a business college and got a job as a stenographer and file clerk for the Santa Fe Railroad.
And in 1918, I registered for the draft in July of 1918, my 20th birthday, and went on down to A&M, though, and enrolled there.
and was inducted into the Army in October of 1918.
It was inducted into the SATC.
Yeah.
And I drew two paydays.
And then, of course, the armistice came.
And they discharged us on the 21st of December.
And I was back home for Christmas in 1918.
So you went down.
Did you go to A&M and enroll?
for school or was the SATC already established when you arrived as a freshman?
It wasn't established, I guess, because I enrolled in school and went there a couple of months before I was inducted.
All of us that were of that age were inducted into the SATC, and the boys that were too young, of course, continued as cadets.
So you were two years older than most of the freshmen.
Yes.
See, I had stayed out of school.
I finished high school in 16 and didn't go to A&M until 18 in order to make enough money to get down there.
And I worked all the time I was there, whatever I could find to do, mowing lawns.
Would this be mowing lawns for the school or for the professors?
Professors.
And, of course, in my...

junior year I was taking civil engineering and I had enough surveying to get a job with the buildings and grounds committee and did some surveying there and set some corners and street markers and things.
This was on the campus?
On the campus for the buildings and grounds department and I also did some typing, sonography work on the side and of course
They had a crew there with tow sacks and sticks with spikes on the end of them to pick up paper and cigarette butts and things, police campus.
I worked at that, oh, two or three hours a week, and swept the military walk from one end to the other, from Speza Hall down to Guyon Hall.
Was it paved in any way at that point?
It was paved.
Guyon Hall was a new hall.
Mm-hmm.
And we got 25 cents an hour for that.
That's for sweeping.
For sweeping or for picking up cigarette butts.
So I got 25 cents an hour for the lawn mowing.
How about for surveying?
I don't remember what I was paid for that, but it was a little more than that.
It was a little more skill required for that, I would think.
Yeah.
I don't remember now what it was.
My dad, of course, helped me all he could.
I'd get enough money to matriculate, sign a note for the difference, and pay it off as I worked along.
Occasionally, he'd send a check, which was pretty... Did you personally sign a note for the difference?
Yeah.
Who sort of underwrote this note?
Nobody.
What I mean is, you signed a promissory note to the school?
Yeah.
And any money you earned was deducted from that amount you owed them?
Well, no, it was paid to me, and I went and paid it off.
I remember one time in particular, I went over there to pay one off, and they said, your dad just sent the money in.
I was real happy about that, of course.
A little pocket change, then.
Yeah.
Okay.
Were there any factors other than the cost at A&M that led you to go there?
Well, of course, I'd heard of A&M and it appealed to me.
I didn't know anybody that had been there, just what I had read about it.
But the cost factor was the main thing.
Did the military appeal to you at all?
Not particularly.
In fact, I got out of the military in my junior year because of a knee injury.
I was no longer able to stay in the military, so I resigned from that and went into the casual hall and finished as a civilian.
So I never did finish the ROTC.
Did you go through any particular procedures to be admitted to the school?
No.
Did you send them a record of your grades or anything, or did you just carry that with you?
I carried it with me, but I didn't have any prior correspondence with them.
I just went off down there and gave them the record that I had, of course.
Was there anybody to meet your train when you arrived there?
No, because we went early, and my roommate and I
We thought we'd go down two or three days early and kind of feel our way around.
Were you able to register immediately, or did they have a certain day set aside?
Oh, we registered.
We were a couple of days early.
We registered when we got there.
And we were assigned to a hall.
And as I told you, we went up and picked out a corner room and fixed it up.
But we ended up in the basement.
But by being assigned to a particular dorm, that meant you were assigned to a particular military company.
Yes, Company D. Company D. Infantry.
Were you in that company both years you were in the military?
Yeah.
But, let's see, since they very quickly, after you arrived, you discontinued your regular schooling and got into the SATC.
Until SATC, of course.
Well, it was regular schooling in SATC, except we had a little more drilling and a little more.
So you did go to regular classes?
Oh, yes.
While you were in the SATC.
Couldn't tell any differences as far as that's concerned.
And then, I believe from what I have read elsewhere, when everybody was discharged from that in December or thereabouts.
December 21st.
You came back in January and started kind of a whole new year all over again, I believe, didn't you?
And that's when they decided to separate the
sophomores, put them in a separate hall, put the freshmen in with the juniors and seniors, which wasn't such a good idea.
Well then they made what, a separate company out of all the sophomores?
Yeah.
Except I presume they had some juniors and senior officers.
Oh yeah.
What do you think was the reason behind that?
to stop hazing, cut down on the hazing.
The sophomores were the principal culprits in the hazing business.
However, of course, the juniors hazed us more than sophomores did because they were right in the building with us.
The sophomores would organize and raid the dormitory where we were.
Of course, we'd hear them coming, and those of us that could went to the woods.
What were your first reactions to the school when you arrived there?
Well, I was real pleased with it.
I liked A&M.
And the thing that appealed to me, you couldn't tell the difference between a rich boy and a poor boy.
We all looked alike.
We all dressed alike.
And you never knew anything about what a boy's background was.
It was very democratic.
Well, it was pretty strict on
keeping up the appearance of your uniform?
Oh, yes.
Yes, very strict about our uniforms and our rooms.
Did you have one uniform, two, or three, or how many?
Well, the government issued us one uniform and an overcoat and a poncho.
We wore ponchos instead of raincoats, and of course had to wear hats.
I had two or three uniforms of my own.
Of course khaki uniform then wasn't very expensive.
So you did have ample opportunity to have your uniform cleaned occasionally?
Oh yeah.
They had laundry service.
They'd back the laundry truck up there every Monday or Tuesday, Wednesday, whatever day.
You'd put your laundry out on the stoop and they'd pick it up and return it.
That was all part of the
whole deal.
I take it your uniform was identified some way so that they could.
Oh yeah it was all marked just like you'd send it to a laundry here.

When I went down there I had two or three silk shirts happened to be a vogue then for boys to wear silk shirts which were pretty expensive but I had bought two or three of them and after I matriculated I decided that
course we all figured that we'd be in France before the year was out because they were sending them over just fast to get them ready.
So we took our shirts down to the mess hall and sold them to the Mexicans.
A silk shirt that had cost us ten dollars we sold for two or three dollars to the Mexican help down there.
But of course as soon as we got out of the
As soon as we were discharged, we were sorry we had done that.
Then we had to go buy everything back, but I didn't buy any more silk shirts.
Were you permitted to have refinements, let us say, like a silk shirt as part of your uniform?
Oh, no.
No, these were civilian.
You just wore this when you were off campus or something?
Yeah.
We couldn't wear them on the campus at all.
When we went home at Christmas, we could wear them,
or went off the campus, we could wear them, but never on the campus.
It was strictly military.
And they posted guards in all the dormitories in the evening to enforce a curfew.
And we had to walk a certain post, just like a military post would be conducted.
Did you walk a post in your own dormitory or in some other one?
Well, wherever they'd sign you.
As I said a while ago, when you were assigned to the sophomore dormitory, it was pretty rough.
You were at their mercy then.
Yeah.
Did you have one man on each floor of the dormitory, or more than that, or less than that?
Well, it depended on the dormitory, how they were arranged.
In Foster Hall, we just had one man at the floor.
Now, in Mitchell Hall, we had two at the floor.
And we had to walk the post, walk back and forth all the time with a rifle.
Of course, it was not loaded.
It didn't have a bayonet or anything, but it

and you had to learn the general orders and the special orders and if the officer of the day came up you had to salute him and tell him what the general orders were and what the special order if you had any trouble you called this corporal of the guard he'd send some help uh did you if you had a or assigned guard duty did you do the whole three-hour trick or whatever it was between uh beginning and the end of quiet hour
They'd come around about once a week.
You'd have to do that.
Certain platoons were assigned a certain days.
I see.
The boys had to be in their rooms at 730.
Everybody, except the seniors, they were exempt because they were all officers.
You didn't have any senior privates?
No.
At various and sundry times, they had
a few senior privates scattered around.
Well, I don't remember any at that time.

Well, of course, that, I suppose, was a little bit different there, at least initially, because a lot of the senior boys who were seniors probably went off directly into the military at the start of their senior year.
In fact, there were very few seniors, very few juniors, and very few seniors up until Christmas, until after the armistice was signed.
The sophomores pretty well ran things the first few months.
Must have been quite a blow to then have the upperclassmen come back after Christmas, wasn't it?
Yeah.
Could you describe a typical day while you were there?
And I presume in view of the fact that you were military for two years and civilian for two, there was some difference between them.
Well, of course, they blew revelry about daylight.
We had to stand formation and march to the mess hall, Speza Hall.
Everybody marched down there in formation.
Had breakfast.
And then they left the hall just as they get through and casually go back to the rooms and wait for a class call.
Everything was done by the bugle.
You had to go by the bugle.
No going to class early.
And they called you.
call you to class and you go whatever class you were going.
And certain days during the week, of course, we had to drill during the morning and that was done by bugle call.
They'd blow the bugle and if the weather looked bad, they'd blow overcoat call or raincoat call or whatever and you had to wear an overcoat, whatever.
And at noontime at
When classes were over then, they blew retreat, not retreat, but recall, and you'd go back to the dormitory in formation to go to lunch, march to lunch in formation.
After lunch then, you'd go back to your room, and if you didn't have a class, you were free to do whatever
you wanted to do, go to work, or study, or sleep, or whatever.
And the same thing was done at supper time.
You'd form, again, military formation to go to supper.
And after supper then, you were free until 730.
And you had to be in the room at 730.
You had somebody come by to make sure you were there.
Well, they had guards.
check all the rooms.
And then at 10 o'clock, or I believe it was 9.45 maybe, they blew, I've forgotten the name of the call, but at 10 o'clock was taps.
When they blew taps, all the lights went out and you were supposed to be in bed.
No activities after taps, except seniors, they didn't have to go by that.
And what about the last two years when you were out of the military in the casual dorm?
We had none of that in the casuals.
Obviously you could be awakened by the bugle in the morning.
Oh, yeah.
But we didn't have to march to meals.
We'd just get up and go to breakfast or go to meals or miss meal if you want to.
But as long as you were in the military, you had to report and march down there.
You didn't have to eat.
get up and leave if you wanted to.
If you didn't like what they had, you could get up and leave.

Well, a few times they'd feed us, they called it lamb, we called it goat, and on signal everybody would take the platter of lamb out to the middle of the mess hall and dump it all in the floor, ladders of meat and all.
in protest of that.
It was really good food.
They had very good food.
There were a couple of meals you didn't like.
When you were in the casual dorm or non-military dorm, where did you eat?
Did you have a separate section set aside?
We ate in the same hall but had separate tables.
And of course, the athletes had separate tables.
And when I got this knee trouble, a doctor assigned me to a special table, special diet.
And he assigned me to one of the athletes' tables and told me to eat lots of steaks and stuff that the athletes got.
So I did pretty well there.
Yeah.
I was going to say, I imagine that didn't bother you at all, did you?
I believe you said when you arrived a little bit early and you selected your dormitory room, and that was again in what dorm?
That was in Leggett.
Leggett, that was your first year.
And then you had to go down, and you ended up in the basement.
What was the life like in the dormitory there?
Well, it was something, of course, entirely different to what I'd ever been used to.
But you soon got accustomed to it.
It was not bad.
It was really, as I look back on it, a very pleasurable time.
Was there a pretty good deal of difference in life, say, in the military dorm and the non-military dorm?
Oh, yes.
How would you describe the difference?
Well, of course, in the non-military dorm,
He would just like being at home or being in a boarding house.
He didn't have a quiet hour?
No, he didn't have any restrictions at all.
Because most of them were older men that had been in service and had come back, served their time in France or wherever.
But I happened to be there because of an injury.
Anybody that had an injury that prevented him from
Being in the military, you'd be assigned there.
During the time you were there, was there ever any option?
If you had been in the military for two years, could you, without giving any other reason than that you wanted to, drop out of the military for the last two?
Yes, if you had served during the war.
You didn't have to take it at all.
It wasn't required.
Not for any of the four years.

They could have let to do it and of course a lot of the boys that had started out as freshmen and were called overseas and came back, of course they went right back in it because a lot of them liked it.
But supposing a boy came there in say the year 1919, 1920 and had not been in the military, he just finished high school in the spring of 19,
and came there in the fall of 19, was he obligated to do the military for four years?
I understand that he was.
Unless he had a physical excuse.
Yeah.
That was my understanding.
What privileges did the upperclassmen have that were denied to the freshmen?
The sophomores didn't have very much of anything, and the juniors maybe a little more than the sophomores.
The senior was pretty well on his own.
Of course, they were the officers.
They had privileges that we didn't have.
They could go to bond any time they wanted to.
We couldn't get off the campus without a pass any time.
And they were not allowed to have a car or even a motorcycle on the campus.
Did you have a bicycle?
Well, I don't remember any that the students had.
I remember some of the professors used bicycles.
This would be to go from their residence to the classroom.
Most of the professors at that time lived on campus.
Were there very many of them that had bicycles?
No, the majority of them did not, but there were a few that did.
Bicycles were not, I gather at that point, not a very
prevalent means of transportation anyway.
Many of the professors have cars?
No, very few of them did.
For most everybody then it was on foot.
They ran an interurban car from College Station to Brown.
That's the way we got over to Bryan.
When we'd get a pass, you'd have to get a pass to go to Bryan or get off the campus.
This was as long as you were in the military, you had to have a pass.
Yeah.
Casuals did not have to.
What was this, an electric interurban or gasoline?
Electric.
Any recollection of how much it cost you to ride over to Bryan?
No, I don't remember.
I guess about 15 cents, but I don't know.
For what purposes would people go over to Bryan?
Oh, just to get off the campus.
Go to the picture show.
We could go over there and go to the show.
If you got back before taps.
That was anybody other than freshmen, I presume, could do that.
Yeah, freshmen couldn't get it.
Well, sometimes if you had relatives there or somebody special, freshmen could get a pass to get off.
But it's very rare.
Was there any place on or near the campus that, say, a parent who came down to see their children, was there any place they could stay?
Yes, there were some places there.
The YMCA had a few rooms.
My mother came down and, well, my father was down there once.
They stayed at the YMCA.
And there were some other places there.
And I think some of the professors
rented rooms to visitors, but you could always find a place in Brown.
When you were in the non-military group your last two years, the dormitory you lived in was Milner Hall.
Was that the only dormitory for non-military or did they have any other?
I asked at one point, I know they had a couple that were called Alpha and Beta.
Two wooden structures.
Well, I don't know about that.
That could have been...
I believe those were in the mid-20s sometime.
Must have been later.
However, they still had some of the old military barracks there, but I don't know what use they put them there.
That would have been barracks that they erected for the regular army who were on campus in 18.
Yeah.
What did you do for entertainment or recreation?
Well, there wasn't a whole lot that we could do.
They had about once a week, they'd have a picture show, a free picture show.
Where was that?
Well, it was in a sort of pavilion.
I've forgotten what they called the thing.
Was that the one they called the air dome?
Air dome.
And, oh, once or twice a year they'd have dances.
Of course, the Ross Volunteers always had some things going.
I didn't belong to the Ross Volunteers.
But what they had was only for the members of that group, not for everybody else.
And they had the...
But our time was pretty well taken up, the time you got through the day and got all your studying and your lab work done and your studying for the next day.
It was time for taps.
Were there any facilities in the Y for playing games or anything of that nature?
Was the swimming pool in the Y when you were there?
Yeah.
Was that free or did you have to pay for that?
I don't know.
I never did use it.
I don't know whether it was free or not.
I wasn't much of a water dog.
What else did they have there besides that?
Well, they had game rooms where they played different games, dominoes and checkers and things of that nature.
